Barplot

# ?barplot
barplot(total_resultados)

# Salvar o plot em disco
png("barplot1.png", width = 480, height = 480 )

        col = rgb(0.5,0.1,0.6,0.6), 
        xlab = "Categorias", 
        ylab = "Valores",

        ylim = c(0,60) )

# Ggplot2 
library(ggplot2)
# Barplot with ggplot2 and mtcars dataset
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = as.factor(cyl), fill = as.factor(cyl) )) +  
  geom_bar( ) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("red", "green", "blue")) # add cores

# Dummy data
dados = data.frame(group = c("A ","B ","C ","D ") , value = c(33,62,56,67))
head(dados)
##   group value
## 1    A     33
## 2    B     62
## 3    C     56
## 4    D     67
# Barplot
ggplot(dados, aes(x = group, y = value ,fill = group )) + 
  geom_bar(width = 0.85, stat = "identity")

Histograma

# Data
x <- mtcars$mpg 
# Criar histograma (criando graf e salvando em uma var)
# ?hist
h <- hist(x, 
          breaks = 10, 
          col = "blue", 
          xlab = "Kilometros Por Hora", 
          main = "Histograma com Curva de Distribuio") 

library(ggplot2)

# data
dados = data.frame(value = rnorm(10000)) #rnom -> cria dados randomicos com distrb normal  
head(dados)
##        value
## 1 -0.9248732
## 2  2.7852763
## 3  0.6168324
## 4  1.8928954
## 5 -0.1228601
## 6  0.2449367
# Tamanho das colunas
ggplot(dados, aes(x=value)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.05)

# Cor uniforme
ggplot(dados, aes(x=value)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.2, color="white", fill=rgb(0.2,0.7,0.1,0.4) )

# Cor proporcional
ggplot(dados, aes(x=value)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.2, aes(fill = ..count..) )

Pie Chart

# ?pie
pizza <- c(10, 12, 15, 16, 33, 20)
paises <- c("Espanha", "Brasil", "Itlia", "Grcia", "Portugal", "Argentina")
pie(pizza, labels = paises, main = "Horas de Caminhada Por Pessoa/Semana")

# Pie Chart 3D
# install.packages("plotrix")
library(plotrix)
# ?pie3D
pizza <- c(10, 12, 15, 16, 33, 20)
paises <- c("Espanha", "Brasil", "Itlia", "Grcia", "Portugal", "Argentina")
pie3D(pizza, labels = paises, explode = 0.1, main = "Horas de Caminhada Por Pessoa/Semana")

Line Chart

# Data
bikes <- c(1, 3, 6, 4, 9, 12, 15, 23)
carros <- c(2, 4, 5, 7, 9, 13, 23, 28)
# Plot
plot(bikes, type = "o", col = "blue", ylim = c(0,25))

lines(carros, type = "o", pch = 22, lty = 2, col = "red")

title(main = "Meios de Transportes", col.main = "red", font.main = 4)

Treemap

#install.packages("treemap")
library(treemap)
# Data
group = c(rep("grupo-1",4), rep("grupo-2",2), rep("grupo-3",3))
subgrup = paste("subgroup", c(1,2,3,4,1,2,1,2,3), sep = "-")
valor = c(13,5,22,12,11,7,3,1,23)
dados = data.frame(group, subgrup, valor)
head(dados)
##     group    subgrup valor
## 1 grupo-1 subgroup-1    13
## 2 grupo-1 subgroup-2     5
## 3 grupo-1 subgroup-3    22
## 4 grupo-1 subgroup-4    12
## 5 grupo-2 subgroup-1    11
## 6 grupo-2 subgroup-2     7
# Labels
# ?treemap
treemap(dados, 
        index = c("group", "subgrup"),     
        vSize = "valor", 
        type = "index",
        fontsize.labels = c(15,12),               
        fontcolor.labels = c("white", "orange"),    
        fontface.labels = c(2,1),                 
        bg.labels = 220,             
        align.labels = list(c("center", "center"), c("right", "bottom")),                                  
        overlap.labels = 0.5,           
        inflate.labels = F)

# Customize the plot above
treemap(dados, 
        index = c("group", "subgrup"), 
        vSize = "valor", 
        type = "index",
        border.col = c("black", "white"),          
        border.lwds = c(7,2))

Boxplot (Analise Univariada)

# library(ggplot2)
# View(mpg) -> Dataset

# Plot
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = reorder(class, hwy), y = hwy, fill = class)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  xlab("class") +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Scatter Plot (Analise Bivariada)

# library(ggplot2)

data = data.frame(cond = rep(c("condition_1", "condition_2"), each=10), 
                  my_x = 1:100 + rnorm(100,sd=9), my_y = 1:100 + rnorm(100,sd=16))

head(data)
##          cond      my_x       my_y
## 1 condition_1 -8.055032 -15.808093
## 2 condition_1  4.380327  24.301169
## 3 condition_1 -8.418623  10.207761
## 4 condition_1  6.407456  26.974891
## 5 condition_1  6.646579  -1.813816
## 6 condition_1  6.233058  37.163968
# Scatterplot
ggplot(data, aes(x=my_x, y=my_y)) + 
  geom_point(shape=1)

# Adicionar uma linha de regresso (lm = linear model)
ggplot(data, aes(x=my_x, y=my_y)) +    
  geom_point(shape=1) +  
  geom_smooth(method = lm , color="red", se=FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

# Adiionar um smooth (intervalo de confiana)
ggplot(data, aes(x=my_x, y=my_y)) +    
  geom_point(shape=1) +  
  geom_smooth(method=lm , color="red", se=TRUE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

## Histograma com Curva de distribuio

x <- mtcars$mpg 

h <- hist(x, 
          breaks = 10, 
          col = "blue", 
          xlab = "Milhas Por Galo", 
          main = "Histograma com Curva de Distribuio") 



# Curva de distribuio 
xfit <- seq(min(x), max(x), length = 40) 
yfit <- dnorm(xfit, mean = mean(x), sd = sd(x)) 

yfit <- yfit*diff(h$mids[1:2])*length(x) 

lines(xfit, yfit, col = "red", lwd = 2)

End
